{
  "texts": [
    "Two vertices are linked if the data points they represent are close in their respective spaces, usually determined by a common distance measure such as the Euclidean distance [46].",
    "When searching for a specific query point, the process typically begins from a set of initial points or seeds.",
    "These seeds can be chosen randomly or based on certain criteria.",
    "The search uses one of these seeds as an entry node and the others as initial candidate answers.",
    "It then progresses by visiting the neighboring vertices of the current node in a best-first, greedy manner, concluding when no better matches are identified [119]."
  ]
}